What Is Already Good
The basic end-to-end path exists and is understandable: user message, agent loop, tool call, persistence, SSE, plan, approval, execution.
The database layer is already acting like the backbone of the app rather than an afterthought. [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/docs/DB_ARCHITECTURE.md](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/docs/DB_ARCHITECTURE.md) and the current backend structure are strong here.
The safety boundary is real, not just prompt text. Execution checks approvals and sandbox constraints before touching files.
Scan persistence is better than it used to be. [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/docs/PHASE_1.7_HANDOFF.md](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/docs/PHASE_1.7_HANDOFF.md) shows that scans, categories, previews, and scan SSE now exist as first-class product pieces.
memory_events already provide useful anti-repeat guardrails in the current flow. [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/propose_plan.py](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/propose_plan.py) uses them to stop the model from planning the same move twice in one session.
Where The Connections Are Weak
1. Scan And Understanding Are Mixed Together
scan_folder currently does all of these at once in [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/scan_folder.py](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/scan_folder.py):
walks the filesystem,
writes scan rows,
upserts file and folder entities,
computes categories and previews,
detects changes,
and returns a model-facing payload.
That means one tool is serving two masters:
the system needs it as an indexer,
the model needs it as a compact understanding primitive.
Those are related, but they should not be the same responsibility.
2. The Loop Still Relies On Transcript Weight
The agent loop and context layer still build intelligence largely by replaying:
full session_messages,
recent tool results,
current task state as JSON text,
active plan text,
recent memory event summaries,
last scan summary.
That works, but it means the loop is paying for context repeatedly instead of asking the database focused questions.
3. Memory Exists In Multiple Forms, But Only Some Of It Is Really Queried
Today AIJAH has four practical memory-like stores:
session_messages: full conversation and tool transcript
task_state: small working memory for the active session
scans plus file_entities and folder_entities: durable filesystem knowledge
memory_events: audit trail of actions and outcomes
The weak connection is that only a small portion of this is really used as retrieval:
task_state is used directly
last_scan is used directly
recent memory_events are formatted into context and checked in propose_plan
full session_messages are replayed heavily
What is mostly missing is a narrow retrieval layer over indexed file data. Right now the model is better at writing to memory than asking memory precise questions.
What Memory Is For Right Now
Working Memory
task_state is the live scratchpad for the session:
current goal,
current step,
active plan id,
scratchpad summary.
This is useful and worth keeping. It is small and directly operational.
Conversation Memory
session_messages are currently serving two purposes:
user-visible conversation history,
model replay context.
That second purpose is what becomes expensive. The transcript is useful, but it should not be the main long-term intelligence layer.
Why it exists at all:
it is the simplest canonical record of what happened in the session,
it lets the UI reconstruct the conversation,
it lets the backend replay tool-call and tool-result sequences in provider-compatible format,
and it preserves short-term conversational continuity without requiring a separate summarization system first.
Why it becomes the wrong default:
it stores everything, including bulky tool output,
it duplicates knowledge that already exists in better structured tables,
and it makes the model re-read history instead of ask focused questions.
Filesystem Memory
scans, file_entities, and folder_entities are the most promising memory system you already have.
They can become the source of truth for questions like:
what folders exist here,
what file types dominate this area,
what changed since last scan,
what files look like duplicates,
what paths already appear organized.
This is the part that should eventually carry more of the model’s understanding burden.
Action Memory
memory_events currently work more like an audit and safety memory than a reasoning memory:
what action ran,
what changed before and after,
whether it succeeded,
which paths should not be proposed again right away.
That is already useful, but it is not yet a true “memory query system.” It is mostly a write-heavy log with a few guardrail reads.
Memory Map
This is the plain-language map of the memory layers that exist today.
1. session_messages
What it is:
the full session transcript
user messages, assistant replies, tool calls, and tool results
What writes it:
run_agent_loop() persists new user messages, assistant messages, and tool results in [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/agent/loop.py](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/agent/loop.py)
What reads it today:
the UI when restoring or displaying conversation history
assemble_context() when rebuilding conversation context for the next model call
provider adapters when reconstructing tool-call sequences, especially Anthropic-compatible replay
Why it exists:
it is the canonical transcript of what happened in a session
it supports user-visible continuity
it preserves exact tool-use history
What is good about it:
simple
complete
useful for debugging and replay
What is weak about it:
it is too expensive to treat the whole transcript as model context every turn
it stores bulky tool outputs that duplicate structured DB knowledge
it blurs user history and model reasoning context into one thing
What it should become:
the canonical transcript and audit trail
a short-window source for conversational continuity
not the primary long-term memory layer for reasoning about files
2. task_state
What it is:
per-session working memory
the current scratchpad for what the assistant is doing right now
What writes it:
the agent loop for state transitions
update_task_state
propose_plan
execution paths that update current step and active plan
What reads it today:
assemble_context()
tool and execution code
any flow that needs the current session goal, step, or active plan
Why it exists:
the agent needs a compact place for live working context that is smaller than the transcript
What is good about it:
small
operational
directly useful for continuity within one task
What is weak about it:
current_step is text-backed and looser than the docs imply
it mixes safety-relevant state with assistant scratchpad behavior
What it should become:
the compact live working-memory layer
small enough to stay in the hot context path
stricter about which fields are authoritative versus advisory
3. scans
What it is:
durable records of scan runs
metadata about when a path was scanned, at what depth, and what was found
What writes it:
scan_folder in [C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/scan_folder.py](C:/Users/jaham/aijah/backend/tools/scan_folder.py)
What reads it today:
assemble_context() for the “Last scan” block
REST endpoints for scan history
frontend scan views
Why it exists:
the system needs a durable record of filesystem observations across time
What is good about it:
first-class scan history now exists
useful for scan lifecycle, counts, categories, and change tracking
What is weak about it:
it is only lightly used as reasoning input today
the model still relies too much on raw tool output instead of querying scan-derived knowledge
What it should become:
the session and device-level index history layer
the entry point for “what changed” and “what do we know about this area” questions
4. file_entities
What it is:
the structured memory of known files on a device
canonical paths plus metadata such as filename, extension, category, preview, existence status
What writes it:
scan_folder
execution paths that update entities after file operations
What reads it today:
read_file_metadata
execution logic when mapping actions back to tracked entities
some backend flows that resolve targets
Why it exists:
the app needs a durable indexed model of the filesystem, not just a conversation about it
What is good about it:
this is one of the most valuable structured-memory layers in the system
it can support narrow retrieval, duplicate detection, and organization analysis
What is weak about it:
there is not yet a strong general retrieval tool over it
the model cannot ask rich questions over indexed files very well
What it should become:
the main factual memory for files
the basis for targeted retrieval instead of transcript replay
5. folder_entities
What it is:
the structured memory of known folders on a device
canonical path hierarchy and folder identity
What writes it:
scan_folder
execution paths when folders are created or moved
What reads it today:
folder-related backend and API views
scan summaries
some plan target resolution flows
Why it exists:
folder structure is the skeleton of filesystem reasoning
What is good about it:
it gives the system durable folder knowledge beyond one scan result
What is weak about it:
like file_entities, it is under-queried by the model layer
folder understanding still often flows through scan payloads instead of narrow DB retrieval
What it should become:
the main structural memory for folder hierarchy and organization patterns
6. memory_events
What it is:
the action and outcome log
pre-state, intended change, action taken, post-state, and outcome
What writes it:
execution flows, especially execute_action
What reads it today:
assemble_context() for recent action summaries
propose_plan() to prevent re-planning already successful actions in the same session
Why it exists:
the system needs auditability, safety history, and eventually learning from outcomes
What is good about it:
strong safety and audit value
already useful as a guardrail against redundant actions
What is weak about it:
it is mostly append-only history today
it is not yet a strong semantic or query-driven memory layer
What it should become:
the execution-history and outcome-learning layer
useful for avoiding repeats, understanding prior successes and failures, and later retrieving analogous past work
7. user_preferences and operational_policies
What they are:
durable instruction memory
what the user prefers and what the system must obey
What writes them:
backend write paths and future learning or admin flows
What reads them today:
assemble_context() adds them directly to the system context
Why they exist:
stable behavior should not rely only on the model remembering recent chat
What is good about them:
they are already conceptually in the right place
they are compact and appropriate for direct prompt injection
What is weak about them:
their lifecycle and update policy are not yet the main issue, but they still need clear ownership
What they should become:
the durable preference and policy layer that stays small and high-signal
Memory Layer Summary
These memory types are not interchangeable:
session_messages are transcript memory
task_state is working memory
scans, file_entities, and folder_entities are filesystem memory
memory_events are action-history memory
user_preferences and operational_policies are behavior memory
The main architectural mistake to avoid is treating transcript memory as if it were the same thing as filesystem memory or retrieval memory.
Minimum Strong Tool Set
This is the concrete tool set the architecture appears to want.
1. Index Tool
Purpose: refresh the database’s understanding of a path.
Input: path, scan depth, maybe scan intent
Writes: scans, file_entities, folder_entities
Returns: compact summary plus identifiers, not giant raw payloads
This is the evolved role of scan_folder.
2. Retrieval Tool
Purpose: ask narrow questions against indexed file and folder data.
Examples:
files under a path
files by extension or category
folders with highest file counts
paths changed since last scan
candidate duplicates by size, name, hash, or similarity
This tool is the biggest missing piece right now. read_file_metadata is too narrow to fill this role by itself.
3. Detail Tool
Purpose: inspect one file or a very small set of files more deeply when needed.
current read_file_metadata partly fits here
a future file-preview or content-inspection tool could also live here
This should stay narrow so the model asks for detail only after it has already narrowed the search space.
4. Planning Tool
Purpose: create approval-backed plans only when an operation truly needs explicit structured review.
Use cases:
rename and move many files
archive duplicates
create missing folders and move files into them
Non-use cases:
simple inspection,
asking what exists,
identifying likely duplicates,
answering follow-up questions about a scan.
5. Execution Tool
Purpose: carry out approved actions safely and record the outcome.
This part is already comparatively solid. Execution has the clearest safety boundary in the current architecture.
Proposed Boundary Changes
Keep
DB as source of truth
approval gate for risky changes
sandbox enforcement
scan persistence
SSE-driven frontend activity visibility
Split More Cleanly
indexing from model-facing retrieval
conversation history from retrieval memory
assistant working state from safety-critical lifecycle state
plan generation from simple analysis
Stop Using As The Default Intelligence Path
replaying full tool payloads into session_messages
relying on giant scan outputs for understanding
forcing propose_plan after every meaningful scan
